          <p>
            Exercise here.
          </p>

        </exercise> 

      </subsection>

      <subsection xml:id="subsec-Solving_Linear_Equations_in_one_Unkown">
        <title>Solving_Linear_Equations_in_one_Unkown</title>
        
        <activity> 
          <title><term>Work in Groups</term></title>

          <p>

            <ol>

              <li>

                <p>
                  On one side of a beam balance, place five matchboxes of the same weight.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  On the other side, place two matchboxes.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  To the side with two matchboxes, gradually add grains of sand until the beam balances.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>
                
                <p>
                  From both sides, remove two matchboxes and observe whether the beam balances.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Represent the mass of the added sand with a letter and form an equation involving the letter.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Discuss and share your results with other groups.
                </p>

              </li>

            </ol>

          </p>

        </activity>

          <p>
            <term>Learning Points.</term>
          </p>

          <p>
            The process of solving an equation may involve:
          </p>

          <p>

            <ol>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Substracting a number from both sides of the equation.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Adding a number to both sides of the eqautions.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Dividing both sides of the eqaution by a number.
                </p>

              </li>

              <li>

                <p>
                  Multiplying both sides of the equation by a number.
                </p>

              </li>

            </ol>

          </p>

        <example>

          <statement>

            <p>
              Solve the following equation:
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>x + 4 = 7</m>
            </p>

          </statement>

          <solution>

            <p>
              Subtract <m>4</m> from both sides.
            </p>

            <image source="/linear_inequality_sum.png">
              <shortdescription>Figure showing how to solve linear inequality.</shortdescription>
            </image>

            <p>
              <m>x + 4 -4 = 7 - 4</m>
            </p>

            <image source="/linear_inequality_sum_2.png">
              <shortdescription>Figure showing final answer.</shortdescription>
            </image>

            <p>
              <m>x = 3</m>
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

        <example>

          <statement>
            
            <p>
              Solve <m>5x - 3 = 17</m>
            </p>
            
          </statement>

          <solution>

              <p>
                Add <m>3</m> to both sides,
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>5x - 3 + 3 = 17 + 3</m>
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>5 x = 20</m>
              </p>

              <p>
                Divide both sides by 5
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>\frac{5x}{5} = \frac{20}{5}</m>
              </p>

              <p>
                <m>x = 4</m>
              </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

        <example>
          <statement>
            <p>
              Solve <m> \frac{1}{4}h = 3</m>
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>

            <p>
              Multiply both sides by <m>4</m>,
            </p>

            <p>
              <m> \frac{1}{4}h\times4 = 3\times4</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              <m> \frac{4h}{4} = 12</m>, therefore
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>h = 3</m>
            </p>

          </solution>

        </example>

