        <example>

          <statement>
            <p>
              Makanda and Magut sell exercise books at <m>40</m> shillings per book. Peter bought some exercise books from Makanda's shop and <m>30</m> more from Magut's shop than from Makanda. He spent a total of <m>4 400 </m> shillings. Find the number of books bought from each shop.
            </p>
          </statement>

          <solution>
            <p>
              Let the number of books bought from Makanda's shop be <m>x.</m> Number of books bought from Magut's shop <m>= x + 30.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Amount spent in Magut's shop <m>= 40 (x + 30).</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>= 40 x + 1 200.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Amount spent in Makanda's shop <m>= 40x.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Total amount <m>= 40x + 1200 + 40x.</m> 
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>= 80x + 1200.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Thus <m>80x + 1200 = 4400.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              80x = 4400 - 1200.
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>80x = 3200.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>x = 40.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
              Number of exercise books bought from Makanda's shop <m>= 40.</m>
            </p>

            <p>
                Number of exercise books bought from Magut's shop <m>= 40 + 30 </m>
            </p>

            <p>
              <m>= 70.</m>
            </p>
          </solution>

        </example>

